04226nam a22005535i 9780804792981DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047929817 a10.1515/97808047929812doi  a(DE-B1597)563559  a(OCoLC)1178769946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0080002bisacsh04a1701 aForti, Simona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Demons :bRethinking Power and Evil Today /cSimona Forti. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Dostoevsky Paradigm -- t2. Instincts, Drives, and Their Vicissitudes: Nietzsche and Freud -- t3. Ontological Evil and the Transcendence of Evil -- t4. Thanatopolitics and Absolute Victims -- t5. The Legend of the Grand Inquisitor Reinterpreted from Below -- t6. A Different Genealogy: The Evil of Docility -- t7. Strategies of Obedience and the Ethos of Freedom -- t8. Parrhesia Put to the Test: Practices of Dissidence Between Eastern and Western Europe -- t9. Poor Devils Who "Worship" Life: Us -- tNotes -- tIndex of Names -- tCultural Memory in the Present 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs long as we care about suffering in the world, says political philosopher Simona Forti, we are compelled to inquire into the question of evil. But is the concept of evil still useful in a postmodern landscape where absolute values have been leveled and relativized by a historicist perspective? Given our current unwillingness to judge others, what signposts remain to guide our ethical behavior? Surveying the nineteenth- and twentieth-century Western philosophical debates on evil, Forti concludes that it is time to leave behind what she calls "the Dostoevsky paradigm": the dualistic vision of an omnipotent monster pitted against absolute, helpless victims. No longer capable of grasping the normalization of evil in today's world-whose structures of power have been transformed-this paradigm has exhausted its explanatory force. In its place, Forti offers a different genealogy of the relationship between evil and power, one that finally calls into question power's recurrent link to transgression. At the center of contemporary evil she posits the passive attitude towards rule-following, the need for normalcy, and the desire for obedience nurtured by our contemporary mass democracies. In our times, she contends, evil must be explored in tandem with our stubborn desire to stay alive at all costs as much as with our deep need for recognition: the new modern absolutes. A courageous book, New Demons extends an original, inspiring call to ethical living in a biopolitical age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEthics, Moderny19th century. 0aEthics, Moderny20th century. 0aGood and evil. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPower (Philosophy) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Good & Evil.2bisacsh1 aHanafi, Zakiya08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479298140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792981.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles